                     <h2>WHAT IS THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN EXTRACTS & FLAVOR EMULSIONS?</h2>
                     <p>Flavoring emulsions are water-based flavor agents, whereas extracts are alcohol-based flavoring agents. When using flavor emulsions for high-heat applications, you don’t have to worry about the flavor “baking out” as water-soluble ingredients don’t evaporate as quickly as the alcohol in the <%= link_to "flavor extracts", (Spree::Taxon.find_by_name("Flavor Extracts").present? ? seo_url(Spree::Taxon.find_by_name("Flavor Extracts")): '/')  %>. The result of the end product is a more potent flavor in your baked goods when using bakery emulsions. Flavoring your treats with Nature’s Flavors baking emulsions allows you to taste test the creation and have a good idea if it needs more flavor emulsions added as well as how it will taste when it’s done.</p>
                  </div>
               </div>

               <div class="block d-flex flex-wrap">
                  <div class="flex-fill">
                     <h2>WHAT IS IN A FLAVORING EMULSION?</h2>
                     <p>A flavor emulsion is a flavor that is suspended in a base of water and vegetable gum. Flavoring emulsions have a thick consistency and mix well into baking applications. The water base also doesn’t add any additional flavor to the flavoring emulsion, so you have a natural flavor in your baked goods. At Nature’s Flavors, our flavor emulsions are made from the finest natural and organic ingredients.</p>
                  </div>
               </div>

               <div class="attention-note">
                  <h2>OVER FLAVORING YOUR PRODUCT WITH FLAVORING EMULSIONS</h2>
                  <p>You have over-flavored your product with flavor emulsions if you notice a minty or medicinal taste. If you are burping up the flavor over an hour after eating the delicious food, you most likely over-flavored it. Always start by using the minimum amount of flavoring emulsions, and taste the food as you go, adding a small amount if desired. The key is not to overdo it with the flavor emulsions and create a finished product that tastes great and leaves people wanting more.</p>
               </div>

